{"action": "edit", "code": "def is_path_exist(input_grid: np.ndarray, square1: Tuple[int, int, int, int], square2: Tuple[int, int, int, int]) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid as a numpy array, two tuples representing the locations of the red grids in the input grid,\n    and returns a boolean value indicating whether there is a path of color teal from square1 to square2.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    square1: A tuple containing 4 elements representing the locations of the red grids in the input grid.\n    square2: A tuple containing 4 elements representing the locations of the red grids in the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether there is a path of color teal from square1 to square2.\n    \"\"\"\n    visited = set()\n    queue = [square1]\n    while queue:\n        curr = queue.pop(0)\n        if curr == square2:\n            return True\n        if curr in visited:\n            continue\n        visited.add(curr)\n        i, j = (curr[0], curr[1])\n        if i > 0 and input_grid[i - 1][j] == teal:\n            queue.append((i - 1, j))\n        if i < input_grid.shape[0] - 1 and input_grid[i + 1][j] == teal:\n            queue.append((i + 1, j))\n        if j > 0 and input_grid[i][j - 1] == teal:\n            queue.append((i, j - 1))\n        if j < input_grid.shape[1] - 1 and input_grid[i][j + 1] == teal:\n            queue.append((i, j + 1))\n    return False\ndef split_positions(positions: List[Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int, int, int], Tuple[int, int, int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a list of tuples representing the locations of all the red grids in the input grid and splits them into two parts.\n    The elements in one part are similar and differs with each other by 1 in row or column.\n    \n    Args:\n    positions: A list of tuples representing the locations of all the red grids in the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two tuples, each containing 4 elements representing the locations of the red grids in the input grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    sorted_positions = sorted(positions)\n    if sorted_positions[0][0] == sorted_positions[1][0]:\n        return ((sorted_positions[0], sorted_positions[1], sorted_positions[2], sorted_positions[3]), (sorted_positions[4], sorted_positions[5], sorted_positions[6], sorted_positions[7]))\n    else:\n        return ((sorted_positions[0], sorted_positions[2], sorted_positions[4], sorted_positions[6]), (sorted_positions[1], sorted_positions[3], sorted_positions[5], sorted_positions[7]))\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    positions = find_red_grids(input_grid)\n    square1, square2 = split_positions(positions)\n    exist = is_path_exist(input_grid, square1, square2)\n    output = color_grid(exist)\n    return output\ndef find_red_grids(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid as a numpy array and returns the locations of all the red grids in the form of a list of tuples.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A list of tuples representing the locations of all the red grids in the input grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    red_grids = []\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == red:\n                red_grids.append((i, j))\n    return red_grids\ndef color_grid(exist: bool) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a boolean value indicating whether there is a path of color teal from square1 to square2 in the input grid,\n    and returns a 1*1 numpy array with color teal if exist is True, and color black if exist is False.\n    \n    Args:\n    exist: A boolean value indicating whether there is a path of color teal from square1 to square2 in the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A 1*1 numpy array with color teal if exist is